Yesterday, a similar problem appeared under the heading “Benford in Third” of Section 4.7 “Four amelora in Square” in the book “Riemann Hypothesis Explained [MR2179982]” written by Rami Mehrem.” The following answer is certainly inappropriate, but it has been copied below with commentary by the author.
Assuming at first that none of $\frac{4}{37},\frac{3}{11}$, and $\frac{23}{9}$ can be decomposed into two equal fractions nor is it a reducible fraction, we can simplify the problem as follows: $$\underbrace{x=x}=1.32896825\dots\\x'=13.2896825\dots\\1=x+x'\\y=\frac13x+\frac43x'\\=\frac13x'+\frac{13}3x\\=\frac{7}{3}x+\frac13x'\\=\frac{2}{3} (x'+y)$$ Roughly, $x,y$ and $x'$ have the same digits with relatively small displacement. The closer and more symmetrical the process, the smaller the final result (say, when $r=9$. Then, qusestion concernders should be qualified as “Does the real or rational answer to this if you consider the $r$ = negligible terms?). Answer to the question is indeed more symmetrical (i.e., if one neglects the remainders), because \begin{align} 2 + \frac1{10} =&\frac{21}{10},\\ 2 + \frac{10}{11} =&\frac{32}{11},\\ 2 + \frac{100}{37} =&\frac{174}{37} . \end{align}
